Solution Part 3: Semantic Updates

06
On this page
  1. Refactor for figure and figcaption Elements
    1. Adding aria-labelledby and aria-describedby for increased labeling information
    2. Updating the Count & Caption
  2. Checking Our Work

We are able to use our Arrow keys to navigate the slideshow and updates are announced. There’s also keyboard focus management in place for when fullscreen mode is opened and closed so users aren’t left in the wrong spot.

Overall, the slideshow works pretty well.

But for navigating through the content on the page, it could be nice to have a more semantic structure. The figure and figcaption elements can provide that.

Refactor for figure and figcaption Elements

In the existing markup, each of the image URLs is mapped over and the following is rendered:

<div 
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`} 
  key={index}
>
  <div className="numbertext">{index + 1} / {images.length}</div>
  <img src={imageUrl} alt={image.alt} style={{width: "100%"}} />
  <div className="text">{image.caption}</div>
</div>
<div 
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`} 
  key={index}
>
  <div className="numbertext">{index + 1} / {images.length}</div>
  <img src={imageUrl} alt={image.alt} style={{width: "100%"}} />
  <div className="text">{image.caption}</div>
</div>

There’s a div wrapper that contains another div for the slide number, an image tag with alt text, and another div for the caption.

Adding aria-labelledby and aria-describedby for increased labeling information

We can start by replacing the div wrapper with the <figure> element. This element is used for a self-contained image and caption. Typically, <figure> and <figcaption> alone will be enough for wrapping an image or other piece of standalone content. But because we’re generating a slideshow inside of an ARIA live region, we’ll add some extra functionality to ensure an informative screen reading experience.

To the figure, we’ll add an aria-labelledby attribute that will create a label by referencing content related to both the image and the caption. Unlike aria-label which takes an arbitrary content string, we’ll supply an ID reference value to aria-labelledby by generating a string template that combines the image and caption with the dynamic index.

Adding an aria-describedby works in a similar way, allowing us to create a programmatic announcement of the count by referencing the ID of an element on the page.

Here’s what the opening <figure> tag looks like all together:

<figure
  aria-describedby={`count-${index}`}
  aria-labelledby={`img-${index} caption-${index}`}
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
  key={index}
>
<figure
  aria-describedby={`count-${index}`}
  aria-labelledby={`img-${index} caption-${index}`}
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
  key={index}
>

Updating the Count & Caption

In the original markup there were divs for both the slide count and the image caption.

The div with a class of numbertext can be be changed to a <p> tag and have an id of count-${index} added as a string template.

The caption div can be replaced by the figcaption element and have an ID of caption-${index} added.

These two ids allows the figure’s aria-labelledby to build its string value.

All together, here’s what the figure-based slideshow markup looks like:

<figure
  aria-describedby={`count-${index}`}
  aria-labelledby={`img-${index} caption-${index}`}
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
  key={index}
>
  <p className="numbertext" id={`count-${index}`}>
    {index + 1} of {images.length}
  </p>
  <img 
    src={imageUrl} 
    alt={image.alt} 
    style={{width: "100%"}} 
    id={`img-${index}`} 
  />
  <figcaption 
    className="text" 
    id={`caption-${index}`}
  >
    {image.caption}
  </figcaption>
</figure>
<figure
  aria-describedby={`count-${index}`}
  aria-labelledby={`img-${index} caption-${index}`}
  className={`slide fade ${currentSlideIndex === index ? 'active' : ''}`}
  key={index}
>
  <p className="numbertext" id={`count-${index}`}>
    {index + 1} of {images.length}
  </p>
  <img 
    src={imageUrl} 
    alt={image.alt} 
    style={{width: "100%"}} 
    id={`img-${index}`} 
  />
  <figcaption 
    className="text" 
    id={`caption-${index}`}
  >
    {image.caption}
  </figcaption>
</figure>

Checking Our Work

With all of the changes saved, the slideshow still works.

The major change is what is being read aloud when the content changes within the ARIA live “polite” region.

We accomplished a lot in this challenge! Updating semantics, adding keyboard support, focus management, and a live region…

As you move forward in implementing these kinds of accessible interfaces in your own applications, remember to use semantic elements. Remember to test with Assistive Technology, particularly with daily screen reader users. And remember the rules of using role="application": most likely, don’t!
